5ï¸âƒ£ What is a â€œserviceâ€ in systemd?
Simple meaning:

A service is a program that runs in the background.

Examples:

sshd â†’ allows SSH login

docker â†’ runs containers

nginx â†’ web server

kubelet â†’ Kubernetes node agent

In systemd, services are defined using unit files.

6ï¸âƒ£ What is a systemd unit?
Unit = configuration file

systemd manages different types of units:

Unit Type	Purpose
.service	   background services
.target	   group of services
.mount	   mount points
.socket	   socket-based activation
.timer	   scheduled jobs (like cron)

ğŸ‘‰ Most important for now: .service and .target

7ï¸âƒ£ systemd service file (simple example)

Example: SSH service

ğŸ“ Location:

/usr/lib/systemd/system/sshd.service


ğŸ“„ Content (simplified):

[Unit]
Description=OpenSSH Server
After=network.target

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/sbin/sshd
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Explain line by line:
[Unit]

Description â†’ human-readable name

After=network.target â†’ start SSH after network

[Service]

ExecStart â†’ command to start service

Restart=always â†’ restart if it crashes

[Install]

WantedBy=multi-user.target â†’ start at system boot

8ï¸âƒ£ What is a target?
Target = group of services

Targets define system state.

Common targets:

Target	Meaning
multi-user.target	   Server mode (CLI)
graphical.target	   Desktop mode (GUI)
rescue.target	      Single-user rescue
shutdown.target	   System shutdown

ğŸ‘‰ When systemd reaches a target, it starts all services linked to it.

9ï¸âƒ£ How systemd starts services (dependency logic)

Example:

