1ï¸âƒ£4ï¸âƒ£ One-line summary (remember this)

systemd is the boss process (PID 1) that starts, stops, monitors, and manages everything on a Linux system after the kernel boots.

After the kernel loads, systemd starts and activates the systemâ€™s default target (such as multi-user.target). The target itself does not run a process; 
instead, it groups and triggers multiple services and other units needed to bring the system to an operational state.
